    "conclusion": "Pollard rho is NOT pseudodeterministic: for balanced semiprimes, different random seeds find different factors (p or q) with roughly equal probability. The consistency rate is ~50-70%, not ~100%. Making factoring pseudodeterministic would require a canonical choice (e.g., always return min(p,q)), which requires FINDING both factors or detecting which is smaller. For balanced semiprimes, this is as hard as factoring itself. Factoring appears to be inherently non-pseudodeterministic in the randomized setting."
